% ── ABSTRACT ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are overwhelmingly benchmarked in English, yet a
billion-plus speakers of Indian languages rely on healthcare systems
where consultations happen in Hindi, Telugu, Tamil, and a dozen other
languages. We study whether current open-source LLMs can generate
trustworthy English clinical summaries directly from multilingual
doctor--patient dialogues---a practically important setting that has
received almost no systematic attention. We evaluate two 7B-parameter
models (Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B) across ten typologically diverse
Indian languages under four conditions: zero-shot prompting, few-shot
prompting with same-language demonstrations ($k{=}2$), translation of
source dialogues to English via IndicTrans2 before summarization, and
LoRA-based supervised fine-tuning.

We find that few-shot prompting with same-language demonstrations
\emph{hurts} rather than helps in 16 of 20 language--model pairs,
with hallucination rates rising 3.4--4.6 percentage points even when
the model sees demonstrations in the test language itself. This
challenges a common assumption in multilingual in-context learning.
Translation through IndicTrans2 improves performance for Indo-Aryan
languages---sometimes substantially---but \emph{degrades} it
severely for Dravidian languages, with Qwen-Telugu dropping
$-0.209$ F1 as translation errors compound into fabricated clinical
content. Across every condition and both models, clinical Safety
scores never reach 3.0 out of 5.0, indicating a persistent gap
between factual plausibility and clinical reliability that
standard prompting cannot close. Supervised fine-tuning remedies
most of these shortfalls: hallucination rates fall from $\sim$42\% to
$\sim$10\% (Qwen) and $\sim$51\% to $\sim$10\% (Mistral), and the
Dravidian performance gap that is stark under prompting ($\sim$0.13
F1 behind high-resource Indo-Aryan) disappears entirely post
fine-tuning. We additionally conduct systematic qualitative case
analysis across all ten languages, yielding an eight-category
Clinical Error Taxonomy that characterizes failure modes by method
and language family.
\end{abstract}

% ── 1. INTRODUCTION ────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Introduction}

Walk into a primary health centre in rural Tamil Nadu or a government
hospital in Assam and you will find a doctor conducting consultations
entirely in Tamil or Assamese, then switching to English to fill in
the clinical notes. This language switch is not incidental---it
reflects a structural feature of Indian healthcare documentation,
where records are kept in a shared administrative language while
care is delivered in the patient's native tongue. The documentation
step is also where things go wrong. Errors and omissions in clinical
notes remain a leading source of adverse outcomes~\citep{clusmann2023future},
and manual documentation under time pressure exacerbates the problem.

LLM-based clinical dialogue summarization offers a practical route
toward reducing this burden. The task is well-posed: given the raw
transcript of a doctor--patient conversation, generate a structured
clinical summary suitable for the medical record. Recent systems have
shown strong results on English
benchmarks~\citep{tang2023gersteinlab,abacha2023overview,vanveen2023adapted},
and there is a growing literature on what makes such summaries
trustworthy~\citep{FraileNavarro2025,Ferreira2025}. What is almost
entirely absent is any systematic evaluation in Indian languages.
India conducts hundreds of millions of clinical consultations annually
across 22 constitutionally recognized languages spanning four major
families~\citep{gala2023indictrans2}. The absence of multilingual
evaluation is not a minor gap.

This paper attempts to fill it. We study English clinical summary
generation from multilingual doctor--patient dialogues across
\textbf{ten Indian languages}---English, Hindi, Marathi, Bengali,
Tamil, Kannada, Telugu, Gujarati, Dogri, and Assamese---spanning
five script families, two typological groups (Indo-Aryan and
Dravidian), and a range of NLP resource levels from well-resourced
to severely low. The target output is always an English summary,
matching real deployment contexts. We evaluate trustworthiness along
three clinically meaningful dimensions: truthfulness, safety, and
explainability.

Four strategies are compared. \textit{Zero-shot prompting} is the
natural baseline---what happens if you just ask the model? \textit{Few-shot
prompting} with same-language demonstrations tests whether showing the
model examples from the same language helps, which prior work on
monolingual settings suggests it should~\citep{brown2020gpt3}.
\textit{Translation-augmented inference} routes dialogues through
IndicTrans2~\citep{gala2023indictrans2} to English before
summarization, hypothesizing that models perform better in their
strongest language. \textit{Supervised fine-tuning} via
LoRA~\citep{hu2021lora} provides the upper bound with task-specific
adaptation.

We find results that complicate the standard picture in several
ways. Few-shot with same-language demonstrations consistently makes
things worse, not better, for most language--model combinations---a
finding whose explanation requires moving beyond the usual
cross-lingual interference story, since the demonstrations share the
test language. Translation through IndicTrans2 has sharply
language-family-dependent effects: helpful for Indo-Aryan, harmful
for Dravidian. Safety remains the hardest dimension to improve,
persisting below 3.0/5.0 across all eight experimental conditions.
And fine-tuning, while effective, reveals that the Dravidian
performance gap is not inherent to the languages but an artifact of
insufficient task-specific training---given appropriate fine-tuning,
Kannada and Telugu reach F1 scores competitive with English.

Beyond these findings, we contribute a Clinical Error Taxonomy
derived from qualitative case analyses across all ten languages,
identifying eight recurring failure patterns with distinct mechanisms
and clinical risk profiles. We hope this taxonomy is useful to
practitioners building multilingual clinical AI in settings far beyond
India.

\paragraph{Summary of contributions.}
\begin{itemize}
  \item First systematic benchmarking of open-source LLMs on
    clinical dialogue summarization across ten Indian languages,
    including all four Dravidian languages with medium-to-low NLP
    resource availability.
  \item Evidence that same-language few-shot demonstrations
    \textit{consistently degrade} performance, with a mechanistic
    account of why this happens even without cross-lingual
    interference.
  \item A language-family-specific analysis of translation
    augmentation, showing that script-distant Dravidian languages
    are harmed rather than helped by the translate-then-summarize
    pipeline.
  \item A finding that supervised fine-tuning closes the cross-lingual
    gap: post-fine-tuning Dravidian F1 equals high-resource
    Indo-Aryan F1.
  \item An eight-category Clinical Error Taxonomy grounded in
    per-language qualitative case analysis.
\end{itemize}

% ── 2. RELATED WORK ────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Related Work}

\paragraph{Clinical dialogue summarization.}
After early work on extractive and abstractive approaches to
medical conversation summarization~\citep{zeng2020meddialog,tretyak2020combination},
the field gained significant momentum from the MEDIQA-Chat 2023
shared task~\citep{abacha2023overview}, which established standardized
benchmarks for the Dialogue2Note problem. \citet{tang2023gersteinlab}
showed that GPT-3 fine-tuning and GPT-4 in-context learning achieve
strong ROUGE-1 and BERTScore on this benchmark.
\citet{mathur2023summqa} observed that GPT-4 zero-shot summaries
tend to be shorter and more abstractive than expert notes---a
coverage gap we replicate and quantify at scale across ten languages.
\citet{vanveen2023adapted} demonstrated that domain-adapted LLMs
can outperform medical experts on English summarization. More recent
work has started moving beyond English: \citet{FraileNavarro2025}
conducted expert evaluation of LLMs on clinical dialogue
summarization, and \citet{Ferreira2025} studied non-English (Portuguese)
clinical conversations, finding that open-source models struggle with
informal patient--provider dialogues. Neither work addresses Indian
languages or the cross-lingual setting we study. \citet{abrar2025faithful}
propose a cross-lingual summarization framework for consumer health
queries using NER and fine-tuned LLMs, but do not evaluate on
clinical dialogues or Indic languages.

\paragraph{Few-shot learning and its failures.}
The GPT-3 paper~\citep{brown2020gpt3} introduced few-shot in-context
learning as a broadly applicable approach. Subsequent work has been
more cautious. \citet{min2022rethinking} showed that demonstrations
primarily communicate output \emph{format} rather than task
semantics---randomly replacing labels in demonstrations barely affects
performance---suggesting that demonstrations act as structural
priors rather than informational signals. When that prior conflicts
with test instance content, performance degrades. \citet{zhao2021calibrate}
documented three systematic biases introduced by few-shot
prompting (majority label, recency, and common token biases) that
can reduce accuracy by up to 30 percentage points relative to
zero-shot. \citet{lu2022fantastically} showed that example
\emph{ordering} alone causes accuracy to vary from near-random to
near-state-of-the-art. For multilingual settings specifically,
\citet{zhang2024impact} evaluated five models across 56 languages and
found that demonstrations are frequently unhelpful or harmful for
low-resource and script-diverse languages, concluding that
``the importance of demonstrations might be overestimated'' in
multilingual ICL. Our results extend this finding to the clinical
domain with same-language demonstrations, adding a new mechanism
(entity bleeding from same-language demos) to the existing account.

\paragraph{Multilingual NLP for Indian languages.}
\citet{gala2023indictrans2} introduced IndicTrans2, the first NMT
system covering all 22 scheduled Indian languages, trained on 230M
sentence pairs and substantially outperforming prior systems.
For clinical tasks, multilingual resources for Indian languages
remain scarce and mostly limited to entity recognition rather than
summarization~\citep{gaschi2023multilingual}.
\citet{singh2025indihealthbench} is the closest prior work to ours,
evaluating LLMs for clinical translation across Indian languages
and finding sharp performance drops for Dravidian languages---
consistent with our zero-shot results, though we extend evaluation
to summarization and cover more languages and experimental conditions.

\paragraph{Evaluation methodology.}
We use ROUGE-L~\citep{lin2004rouge} and BERTScore~\citep{zhang2020bertscore}
as surface-level metrics, while recognizing their limitations for
clinical evaluation~\citep{mathur2023summqa}. For holistic quality,
we adopt the LLM-as-judge framework from \citet{zheng2023judging},
who showed $>80\%$ agreement with expert evaluators. For
entity-level fidelity, we build on the hallucination-and-omission
analysis framework from \citet{clusmann2023future}.

% ── 3. TASK AND DATA ───────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Task, Data, and Models}

\subsection{Task Definition}

We study \emph{cross-lingual clinical dialogue summarization}: given a
multi-turn doctor--patient dialogue in one of ten Indian languages,
generate a structured English clinical summary. The English output
is the target in all conditions, matching realistic deployment
contexts where medical records are maintained in English while
consultations occur in the patient's native language.

\subsection{Dataset}

We use the dataset from the Shared Task on Patient-Centric Clinical
Dialogue Summarization,\footnote{\url{https://www.codabench.org/competitions/10527/}}
which provides multilingual doctor--patient dialogues paired with
expert-authored English clinical summaries. Dialogues exhibit features
typical of clinical discourse: domain-specific terminology,
code-switching between English and regional languages, and the
asymmetric turn-taking patterns of medical consultations. We evaluate
on 50 held-out examples per language from the training corpus.
