\subsection{Models}

\textbf{Mistral-7B-Instruct}~\citep{jiang2023mistral} uses Grouped
Query Attention and Sliding Window Attention for efficient inference.
Its pretraining is primarily European-centric, which we hypothesize
explains its relatively weaker zero-shot performance on non-Latin-script
languages. \textbf{Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct}~\citep{qwen25techreport} was
trained on 18T tokens with explicit multilingual coverage, including
Indic scripts. Both models fit within a single 32GB GPU, making them
practical for privacy-constrained clinical deployment.

% ── 4. METHODS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Methods}

\paragraph{Zero-shot (ZS).}
The model receives a system prompt instructing it to generate a
structured English clinical summary covering chief complaint, symptoms,
investigations, treatment, and follow-up, without introducing
unsupported medical claims. The system prompt and source dialogue
are the only inputs. This is the primary baseline.

\paragraph{Few-shot (FS).}
We augment the zero-shot prompt with $k{=}2$ complete
demonstration pairs: each consists of a source dialogue and its
gold English summary. A key design choice is that \textbf{demonstrations
are drawn from the same language as the test instance}. A Telugu test
dialogue receives Telugu demonstration dialogues with English summaries;
a Hindi test receives Hindi demonstrations. This eliminates cross-lingual
demonstration interference as a confound and isolates the effect of
providing structural examples. Any degradation observed under this
setting cannot be attributed to language mismatch between demo and
test---it must have another explanation.

\paragraph{Translation (Trans).}
Non-English source dialogues are first translated to English using
IndicTrans2~\citep{gala2023indictrans2}, then summarized under the
same zero-shot English prompt. Since the target output is an English
summary, \textbf{no back-translation is performed}. The translated
English dialogue replaces the source dialogue; everything downstream
is identical to zero-shot. English dialogues bypass this step.
The hypothesis is that routing through English allows models to
summarize in their strongest generation language, compensating for
weaker multilingual generation calibration.

\paragraph{Supervised fine-tuning (SFT).}
We fine-tune both models using LoRA~\citep{hu2021lora} on the full
multilingual training set. We use rank $r{=}16$, $\alpha{=}32$,
dropout $0.05$, applied to the query, key, value, and output
projection layers. Training uses AdamW (8-bit), learning rate
$2{\times}10^{-4}$ with cosine decay and warmup, effective batch size
16, for 3 epochs in bfloat16. At inference, models use the same
prompt template as zero-shot.

\subsection{Evaluation Framework}

We evaluate along three complementary tiers.

\textit{Surface metrics}: ROUGE-L~\citep{lin2004rouge} and
BERTScore~\citep{zhang2020bertscore}. Both are necessary but
insufficient---a model can score well on surface overlap while
hallucinating drug names or omitting diagnoses. We include them for
comparability with prior work.

\textit{LLM-as-judge}: We use GPT-4.1 to score each summary on three
dimensions using structured rubrics (1--5 Likert scale, where 3 is
``acceptable'' and 5 is ``excellent''). \textbf{Truthfulness}: are
all claims medically accurate and grounded in the conversation?
\textbf{Safety}: does the summary avoid omissions, distortions, or
fabrications that could lead to harmful clinical decisions?
\textbf{Explainability}: can a clinical reader trace each substantive
claim back to a specific point in the dialogue, with correct negation,
temporality, and speaker attribution? The judge receives the source
dialogue, the generated summary, and the gold reference
(for orientation only, not as ground truth). Full prompts appear in
Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix}. We do not use fuzzy string matching for
entity evaluation because it falsely penalizes valid clinical synonyms.

\textit{Clinical entity analysis}: GPT-4.1 extracts five entity
categories---Symptoms, Diagnoses, Substances and Habits, Procedures
and Tests, Treatments---from both generated and gold summaries,
normalizing morphological variants to canonical forms. A generated
entity is a true positive (TP) if semantically equivalent to a gold
entity; a false positive (FP, or \textit{hallucination}) if it
appears in the generated but not the gold summary; a false negative
(FN, or \textit{omission}) if a gold entity is absent from the
generated summary. We report Precision, Recall, F1, Hallucination
Rate ($= \text{FP}/(\text{TP}+\text{FP})$), and Omission Rate
($= \text{FN}/(\text{TP}+\text{FN})$).

