This result is harder to explain than it first appears.
The standard account of few-shot degradation in multilingual
settings---cross-lingual interference, where an English demonstration
pulls the model's generation toward English
patterns~\citep{zhang2024impact}---does not apply here, because the
demonstrations share the test language. What is happening instead?

We identify three mechanisms. First, \textit{template lock}: the
demonstration summary encodes a particular clinical narrative
structure, and the model adheres to it even when the test dialogue
contains content that falls outside that structure. Omission rates
increase in 14 of 20 language--model combinations under few-shot.
Second, \textit{entity bleed}: entities from the demonstration
dialogues---patient demographics, medication names, symptom
descriptions---migrate into the generated summary for a different
patient. This inflates hallucination counts with content that is
clinically real but belongs to the wrong case, making the error
invisible to surface-level metrics. Third, \textit{calibration
disruption}: for models already well-calibrated to clinical
summarization at zero-shot, the demonstration introduces a competing
prior that interferes with generation. The English zero-shot condition
illustrates this clearly---Mistral-English F1 drops from 0.652 to
0.558 under few-shot, the largest single degradation in the Mistral
few-shot condition, and precisely where the model is best calibrated.

These mechanisms are consistent with prior work showing that
demonstrations primarily encode format rather than semantic
content~\citep{min2022rethinking}, and that few-shot biases
can actively hurt performance compared to zero-shot when the model's
prior is already reasonable~\citep{zhao2021calibrate}. There are
two exceptions: Qwen-Gujarati (F1 $+0.134$) and Mistral-Telugu
(F1 $+0.096$). Both have the highest zero-shot hallucination rates
in their respective matrices (0.693 and 0.718). Here, demonstrations
constrain otherwise uncontrolled generation---they help precisely
when the alternative is near-random output. This suggests a threshold:
few-shot is beneficial only when zero-shot generation is severely
miscalibrated, otherwise it introduces more noise than signal.

One observation worth noting is that ROUGE-L and BERTScore are nearly
insensitive to the zero-shot/few-shot difference ($\Delta < 0.012$),
while entity-level metrics show meaningful changes. This is a concrete
reminder that surface overlap metrics should not be the primary
evaluation criterion in clinical settings, where the cost of a
fabricated drug name or missed diagnosis far exceeds the cost of
slightly different phrasing.

