Several observations stand out. The largest F1 gains go to the
languages that needed them most. Mistral-Telugu improves by 0.487,
Qwen-Gujarati by 0.406, Qwen-Kannada by 0.371---precisely the
languages where zero-shot performance was lowest. The Dravidian
languages, which averaged F1\,$\approx$\,0.457 (Qwen) and 0.378
(Mistral) at zero-shot, reach 0.781 and 0.772 post fine-tuning,
nearly identical to the IA high-resource group (0.756 and 0.747).
The performance gap that was real and sizable under prompting is
essentially eliminated by fine-tuning. This is an important
result for equity: the gap is not inherent to the languages, it
is an artifact of insufficient task-specific training.

The hallucination reductions are equally striking. Macro-average
hallucination drops from 42.4\% to 10.5\% for Qwen and from 50.9\%
to 9.8\% for Mistral. Mistral-Telugu, which had a hallucination rate
of 71.8\% at zero-shot---meaning nearly three-quarters of generated
clinical entities were ungrounded---falls to 7.0\% post fine-tuning,
below the English zero-shot rate of 29.6\%. After fine-tuning,
every language for both models achieves hallucination below 14.5\%.

Safety scores improve from around 2.5 (Qwen zero-shot) to 2.96
(Qwen SFT) and from 2.5 to 2.92 (Mistral SFT). Importantly, neither
model crosses 3.0/5.0 as a macro-average even after fine-tuning.
More tellingly, the gap between Truthfulness and Safety scores
\emph{widens} under fine-tuning: at zero-shot it is around 0.76
(Qwen) and 0.60 (Mistral); at SFT it grows to 1.19 and 1.17.
Models become more truthful much faster than they become safer.
This dissociation occurs because Safety penalizes not just factual
errors but also actionable omissions, inverted negations, incorrect
dosages, and incomplete management plans---a richer set of clinical
harms that supervised imitation of gold summaries does not directly
optimize for. Closing this gap likely requires safety-specific
training signals, such as rubric-grounded reward models or
reinforcement learning from clinical expert feedback.

\subsection{Qwen2.5-7B Outperforms Mistral-7B, Mainly at Zero-Shot}

At zero-shot, Qwen2.5-7B leads Mistral-7B on every entity-level
metric: F1 0.518 vs.\ 0.432 ($+$0.086), precision 0.576 vs.\ 0.490,
recall 0.484 vs.\ 0.392, hallucination 0.424 vs.\ 0.510.
Qwen also leads on LLM-judge dimensions: Truthfulness by 0.226,
Explainability by 0.336. The one exception is ROUGE-L, where Mistral
is marginally higher (0.1352 vs.\ 0.1318), but this reflects shorter,
more formulaic outputs that happen to share surface n-grams with gold
summaries---not better clinical coverage, as confirmed by lower entity
F1 and BERTScore. Qwen's advantage traces to its broader multilingual
pretraining: its token representations for non-Latin scripts are
better calibrated, giving it stronger generative confidence in
Dravidian and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages.

After fine-tuning, the gap narrows substantially: 0.775 vs.\ 0.760
F1 ($+$0.014). The remaining difference is small and probably reflects
model-specific capacity for clinical summarization rather than
language-family effects. Practitioners working in resource-constrained
settings should prefer Qwen2.5-7B for prompting-based deployment;
for fine-tuned deployment, both models are viable.

\subsection{Safety Is the Hardest Dimension to Improve}

Safety is the lowest-scoring dimension in every single experimental
condition for both models, and it is the only dimension that fails
to reach 3.0/5.0 even after fine-tuning. The scores range from
1.42 (Mistral-Assamese translation) to 3.08 (Qwen-Kannada SFT),
with macro-averages between 2.197 and 2.962. Looking at the
safety-truthfulness gap by condition:

