The gap is widest under SFT, not narrowest. Standard fine-tuning
on gold summaries teaches the model to produce accurate-sounding
content---improving Truthfulness and Explainability---but does not
sufficiently optimize for the absence of dangerous omissions or
clinical distortions. Safety evaluation by an expert judge penalizes
subtle failures that do not show up in n-gram comparison against a
gold reference, such as an inverted negation (``no dysphagia''
becoming ``mild dysphagia'') or a conditional plan (``consider
biopsy if laryngoscopy is abnormal'') becoming a definitive
recommendation (``biopsy is required''). These errors survive
fine-tuning unless the training objective specifically targets them.

The safety deficit is also not uniformly distributed across
languages. At zero-shot, Dravidian languages score notably lower
on Safety (Qwen: 2.23 average) than high-resource Indo-Aryan
languages (Qwen: 2.84 average), reflecting the weaker generative
calibration for these scripts. Under translation, Dravidian and
low-resource languages suffer the most severe safety collapses.
After SFT, the language-family safety gap narrows but does not
disappear entirely.

% ── 6. QUALITATIVE ERROR TAXONOMY ──────────────────────────────
\section{Clinical Error Taxonomy}

To complement the quantitative results, we conducted systematic
qualitative analysis across all ten languages, examining generated
summaries against source dialogues and gold references for each
experimental condition. We identified eight recurring error
patterns, which we organize into a Clinical Error Taxonomy.
The categories are not mutually exclusive---a single summary can
exhibit multiple error types---but they represent distinct mechanisms
and have different clinical consequences.

\paragraph{T1 -- Temporal distortion.}
Numerals are carried over correctly but their temporal units are
substituted: a three-month follow-up cadence becomes three days;
a four-week symptom duration becomes four days. The error is
particularly dangerous because the number looks reasonable while
the timeline is wildly wrong. Common in zero-shot for low-resource
languages, where weaker tokenization leads to loss of temporal
context surrounding a correctly extracted numeral.

\paragraph{T2 -- Pathology fabrication.}
The model generates clinically plausible but entirely invented
diagnoses, symptoms, or comorbidities. In our Telugu zero-shot
case, the patient presented with throat discomfort and voice change;
the model generated ``post-falloff-apnea treatment'' and a four-day
apnea episode. This pattern is most common in zero-shot generation
for Dravidian languages, where lower generative confidence leads the
model to fill representational gaps with content from its clinical
pretraining prior.

\paragraph{T3 -- Entity bleed.}
Clinical entities from demonstration examples migrate into the
generated summary for a different patient. In our Telugu few-shot
case, the generated summary introduced a caregiver named ``Evelyn''
(not mentioned in the test dialogue), a fabricated 25-year smoking
history contradicting the stated ``rare'' cigarette use, and
``hypertension controlled with amlodipine'' for a patient with no
documented comorbidities. This error is exclusive to few-shot
and is present to some degree in all languages. It is particularly
dangerous because the bled content is clinically accurate
information---just about the wrong patient---making it
indistinguishable from correctly extracted content without access
to the original dialogue.

\paragraph{T4 -- Frequency inversion.}
Reported substance use frequencies are minimized or inverted:
alcohol use of 3--4 times per week becomes ``occasional use'';
``rare'' cigarette use becomes 8--12 cigarettes per day. Cessation
advice direction is sometimes flipped (``advise against increasing
use'' instead of ``recommend cessation''). Observed across zero-shot,
few-shot, and translation conditions, and most consequential for
cancer risk stratification and treatment eligibility.

\paragraph{T5 -- Conditionality collapse.}
Conditional clinical plans---``if laryngoscopy shows abnormality,
consider biopsy''---are rendered as definitive statements:
``biopsy is required.'' The clinical decision gate is removed,
which both misrepresents the agreed management and could precipitate
unnecessary procedures. Most common in few-shot (where demonstration
summaries typically describe completed rather than planned
encounters) and in translation (where Dravidian conditional
morphology is lost in the English rendering).

\paragraph{T6 -- Speaker misattribution.}
Clinical advice given by the physician is attributed to the patient,
or patient-reported symptoms are framed as clinician findings.
Primarily observed in translation outputs, where IndicTrans2
frequently drops speaker-role markers encoded grammatically in
Dravidian languages (honorifics, person-marked verb forms) when
rendering into English. The downstream summarizer, seeing a
deattributed English sentence, assigns it to the more prominent
discourse participant.

\paragraph{T7 -- Fabricated absence assertion.}
The model generates a confident negative claim that contradicts
source content: ``side effects were not reported'' when the patient
explicitly lists five. This error is specific to translation outputs
and arises when IndicTrans2 produces degraded or incomplete English
for a symptom-rich passage. The summarizer, unable to extract
content, generates a hedging meta-statement that is factually false
and actively misinforms the reader.

\paragraph{T8 -- Mistranslation cascade.}
An IndicTrans2 translation error produces semantically empty or
nonsensical English, causing the downstream summarizer to either
omit the content entirely or generate a plausible-sounding but
incorrect substitution. Two sub-forms: complete collapse
(``reduce tobacco use'' $\to$ ``reduce their space''$\to$
no tobacco content in summary) and partial mistranslation
(``eligible up to age 45'' $\to$ ``45 individuals per month'').
Most severe for Dravidian languages and Assamese.

These eight error types differ in clinical consequence and in
detectability without access to the source dialogue. T3 (entity bleed)
is arguably the most dangerous in deployed settings: the fabricated
content is medically valid---it just describes the wrong patient---
and cannot be detected by a clinician reading the summary alone.
T7 (fabricated absence) actively inverts documented information.
Both are undetectable without the original dialogue. T1 and T5 are
detectable through clinical implausibility (a three-day follow-up
for a cancer case). T6 and T8 are detectable if the clinician is
familiar with the patient.

% ── 7. DISCUSSION ──────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Discussion}

\paragraph{What this means for equitable healthcare AI.}
Our results put numbers on a structural problem. Dravidian language
users face hallucination rates that are roughly 15 percentage points
higher than English users at zero-shot. Translation, the seemingly
natural solution, makes their situation worse rather than better.
Few-shot prompting, another default approach, degrades performance
across the board. The one strategy that actually works---fine-tuning
on domain-matched multilingual data---requires investment that is
currently not happening at scale for Indian languages. The implication
is that deploying existing English-optimized clinical LLMs for Indian
language settings, without fine-tuning, would produce documentation
that is measurably less safe for speakers of Dravidian languages
than for English speakers. This is not a theoretical concern; it is
a quantified disparity in clinical AI reliability.

\paragraph{The few-shot result and what it tells us about ICL.}
The finding that same-language demonstrations consistently hurt
performance is worth emphasizing because it rules out the most common
explanation for few-shot degradation in multilingual settings. If
cross-lingual interference were the mechanism, same-language
demonstrations should help. They do not. The entity-bleed mechanism
we identify---demonstrations contaminating outputs with entities from
a different patient---suggests a failure mode specific to clinical
settings where documents are domain-homogeneous: every demonstration
dialogue and test dialogue shares the same clinical domain, so
entities can transfer plausibly but incorrectly. This is a warning
for any high-stakes domain where few-shot prompting involves
in-domain demonstrations.

\paragraph{What would close the safety gap.}
Standard supervised fine-tuning on gold summaries improves safety
scores substantially but does not close them to clinically
acceptable levels. The widening safety-truthfulness gap under SFT
suggests that what is missing is not more data but different
feedback: the training objective needs to penalize dangerous
omissions, conditional plan distortions, and negation errors
specifically. Clinician feedback, safety-specific reward models,
or structured evaluation criteria built into the fine-tuning loop
are likely necessary. This is an open problem at the intersection
of clinical NLP and alignment research.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
Our evaluation covers 50 examples per language from a single shared
task dataset; larger-scale evaluation with more diverse clinical
scenarios is needed. We evaluate two 7B models; results may differ
for larger models or models with stronger Indic language pretraining.
The LLM-as-judge dimension is an approximation of expert clinical
evaluation; inter-rater agreement with actual clinicians should be
validated in future work. Our qualitative analysis covers one
representative case per language per method; broader qualitative
coverage could surface additional error types.

% ── 8. CONCLUSION ──────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Conclusion}

We studied the trustworthiness of multilingual clinical dialogue
summarization across ten Indian languages, finding that few-shot
prompting with same-language demonstrations consistently makes things
worse through template lock, entity bleed, and calibration disruption;
that translation through IndicTrans2 helps Indo-Aryan languages but
harms Dravidian and low-resource languages through mistranslation
cascades; and that clinical Safety remains below acceptable thresholds
across all conditions and both models even after fine-tuning. The one
clearly good news is that supervised fine-tuning closes the
cross-lingual performance gap: with appropriate domain-matched
training, Kannada and Telugu reach F1 scores competitive with
English, demonstrating that the gap is not inherent to the languages
but reflects the current state of investment in multilingual clinical AI.

We close with what we think is the main takeaway for the pluralistic
alignment community: safety evaluations for clinical AI that are
conducted only in English will systematically underestimate the risk
faced by speakers of low-resource languages. A system that scores
well on English safety benchmarks may simultaneously be producing
clinical summaries with 70\% hallucination rates in Telugu.
These are not edge cases; they are the majority of India's clinical
interactions. Evaluation frameworks, training datasets, and safety
standards need to reflect that reality.

